extends /views/templates/layouts/_base

append variables
	- pagetitle = "PanelControl | Examples | Wizard"

block content
	.lane
		.container
			.page-header
				h1 Wizard
				p.lead A gated, multi-step flow. PanelControl owns the tab UI, the page owns only the flow.

	+section("Live demo")
		p The PanelSet #[a(href="/panelset/examples/wizard.html") Wizard] wires its tab strip and locking by hand, and ends on a hint: that bookkeeping "belongs in a small reusable tab-strip layer over PanelSet." This page is that layer. PanelControl wires the tab clicks, keyboard navigation, roving #[code tabindex], and the #[code aria-disabled] locking. What is left on the page is purely #[strong flow]: validate a step, decide which tabs to lock, gate forward moves, and step with Previous / Next. That remainder is what a future #[strong PanelFlow] will absorb.

		p A required checkbox on each step gates progress. Because tab clicks, #[code next()], #[code prev()], keyboard and deep links all funnel through #[code show()], a single #[code ps:beforeactivate] listener guards every path. Stepping #[strong back] is always allowed.

		.card
			.demo
				nav.tabs#pcwiz-tabs(role="tablist" data-panelcontrol aria-label="Steps")
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-1" aria-selected="true") Account
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-2") Profile
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-3") Confirm

				#pcwiz(data-panelset data-ps-levels)
					.panel-wrapper
						.active#pcwiz-step-1(role="tabpanel" aria-label="Account")
							h3 Step 1. Account
							label.wizard-check
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I agree to create an account
						#pcwiz-step-2(role="tabpanel" hidden aria-label="Profile")
							h3 Step 2. Profile
							label.wizard-check
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I confirm my profile details are correct
						#pcwiz-step-3(role="tabpanel" hidden aria-label="Confirm")
							h3 Step 3. Confirm
							label.wizard-check
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I accept the terms and conditions

				.wizard-nav
					button.secondary(data-pcwiz-prev) Previous
					button(data-pcwiz-next) Next

			p #[strong Try it]: with the current step unticked, #[strong Next] is blocked and focus jumps to the checkbox. Tick it and the following tab unlocks. A tab further ahead stays locked until you get there.

			h4 Markup
			+codeblock('HTML')
				nav.tabs(role="tablist" data-panelcontrol aria-label="Steps")
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-1" aria-selected="true") Account
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-2") Profile
					button(role="tab" aria-controls="pcwiz-step-3") Confirm
				+n
				#pcwiz(data-panelset data-ps-levels)
					.panel-wrapper
						#pcwiz-step-1.active(role="tabpanel")
							label
								input(type="checkbox" required)
								span I agree to create an account
						#pcwiz-step-2(role="tabpanel" hidden) …
						#pcwiz-step-3(role="tabpanel" hidden) …
				+n
				.wizard-nav
					button(data-pcwiz-prev) Previous
					button(data-pcwiz-next) Next

	+section("The flow logic (the part PanelFlow will own)")
		p PanelControl is wired by the markup alone. It handles tab activation, keyboard navigation, roving, and the #[code aria-disabled] reflection. The page adds only flow:

		+codeblock('JS').
			const strip = document.querySelector('#pcwiz-tabs');
			const pc    = strip.panelControl;        // set by PanelControl.init()
			const setEl = document.querySelector('#pcwiz');
			const tabs  = [...strip.querySelectorAll('[role="tab"]')];
			const nextBtn = document.querySelector('[data-pcwiz-next]');
			const prevBtn = document.querySelector('[data-pcwiz-prev]');

			const panelOf = tab => document.getElementById(tab.getAttribute('aria-controls'));
			const valid   = panel => !panel.querySelector('[required]:invalid');

			// Buttons step through the set. PanelControl already wires the tab clicks + keyboard.
			nextBtn.addEventListener('click', e => setEl.panelSet.next({ event: e }));
			prevBtn.addEventListener('click', e => setEl.panelSet.prev({ event: e }));

			// Hard gate: one listener covers every path into show().
			setEl.addEventListener('ps:beforeactivate', e => {
				const { outgoingPanel, targetPanel } = e.detail;
				const forward = outgoingPanel &&
					(outgoingPanel.compareDocumentPosition(targetPanel) & Node.DOCUMENT_POSITION_FOLLOWING);
				if (forward && !valid(outgoingPanel)) {
					e.preventDefault();
					outgoingPanel.querySelector('[required]:invalid')?.focus();
				}
			});

			// Soft state: lock the steps beyond the first incomplete one, through PanelControl.
			function refresh() {
				const firstInvalid = tabs.findIndex(t => !valid(panelOf(t)));
				tabs.forEach((t, i) => pc.setTabState(
					t.getAttribute('aria-controls'),
					firstInvalid !== -1 && i > firstInvalid ? 'disabled' : 'enabled'
				));
			}
			setEl.addEventListener('change', refresh);
			setEl.addEventListener('ps:activationcomplete', refresh);
			refresh();

		p Next to the #[a(href="/panelset/examples/wizard.html") hand-wired PanelSet version], the tab click handlers and the keyboard logic are gone, and locking goes through #[code setTabState()] (which also keeps the roving #[code tabindex] correct) instead of poking #[code aria-disabled] directly. The validation and the lock policy stay on the page. That is the seam: #[strong PanelControl owns the UI, the page owns the flow]. PanelFlow will package this remainder. The Previous / Next end-disabling is the same as the PanelSet wizard, so it is left out above.

	+section("What is not solved yet")
		p Two rough edges show on purpose. They are what the future PanelFlow work (plus one small addition to PanelControl) will tidy up:
		ul
			li #[strong A locked tab is silent.] Clicking a locked tab does nothing and says nothing. The #[strong Next] button, by contrast, hits the #[code ps:beforeactivate] gate and focuses the missing field. A future #[code pc:lockedactivation] event would give the locked-tab click the same chance to explain itself.
			li #[strong Arrow keys skip locked tabs.] Today a locked tab leaves the roving order, so arrows jump over it. For a wizard you might prefer to arrow #[em onto] a locked step to read it, while still refusing to activate it. That is a behaviour choice for PanelFlow to make, not a fixed rule.


append styles
	style.
		#pcwiz {
			--ps-panel-in-transform-from: translateX(40px);
			--ps-panel-out-transform-to:  translateX(-40px);
			--ps-panel-in-delay: 0s;
			border: 1px solid var(--border-default);
			border-radius: 8px;
			padding-top: 0;
		}
		#pcwiz .panel-wrapper [role="tabpanel"] {
			padding: 1.25rem;
		}
		.wizard-nav {
			display: flex;
			justify-content: space-between;
			gap: 0.5rem;
			margin-top: 0.75rem;
		}
		.wizard-check {
			display: flex;
			align-items: center;
			gap: 0.5rem;
			margin-top: 0.75rem;
		}
		.tabs [role="tab"][aria-disabled="true"] {
			opacity: 0.4;
			cursor: not-allowed;
		}


append scripts
	if isProd
		script(src=`${basePath}lib/panelset.js` vite-ignore)
		script.
			PanelControl.init();
			PanelSet.init();
		script(src=`${basePath}assets/scripts/example-pcwizard.js` vite-ignore)
	else
		script(type="module").
			import { PanelSet, PanelControl } from 'panelset';
			PanelControl.init({ debug: true });
			PanelSet.init({ debug: true });
		script(type="module" src="/src/assets/scripts/example-pcwizard.js")
